{"title_page": "Ren\u00e9e Gilly", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ren\u00e9e Gilly\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1906|04|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Paris, France\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1977|03|31|1906|04|29|df=y}}\n| death_place = Paris, France\n| other_names =\n| education   =\n| occupation  = {{plainlist|\n* Operatic [[mezzo-soprano]]\n* Academic teacher\n}}\n| spouse      = [[Louis Musy]]\n| parents     = [[Dinh Gilly]], [[C\u00e9cile Gilly]]\n| nationality = [[France]]\n}}\n'''Ren\u00e9e Gilly''' (19 April 1906&nbsp;\u2013 31 March 1977) was a French operatic [[mezzo-soprano]]. She was a long-time principal member of the [[Op\u00e9ra-Comique]], where she performed leading roles such as Massenet's [[Werther|Charlotte]], Mascagni's [[Cavalleria Rusticana|Santuzza]], and Bizet's [[Carmen]]. She appeared in world premieres and sang as a guest at major opera houses in Europe.\n\n== Career ==\nGilly was born in Paris, the daughter of [[baritone]] [[Dinh Gilly]] and mezzo-soprano [[C\u00e9cile Gilly]].{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}  At the age of four she began piano studies with [[Marguerite Long]].{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} In 1922 at the age of 16 she undertook a series of piano recitals in England. She also served as an accompanist to her father, who participated in a series of conferences concerning singing.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} At the suggestion of [[Pierre-Barth\u00e9lemy Gheusi]] (later director of the [[Op\u00e9ra-Comique]]) she took up singing, studying with both her father and her mother.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|p=1730}}\n\nShe made her debut at the Op\u00e9ra-Comique in the role of Charlotte in Massenet\u2019s ''[[Werther]]'' on 16 September 1933 and became one of the company's central  performers.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} Among her roles there were Bizet's [[Carmen]], Santuzza in Mascagni's ''[[Cavalleria Rusticana]]'', Toinette in [[Xavier Leroux]]'s ''Le Chemineau'', Dulcin\u00e9e in Massenet's ''[[Don Quichotte]]'', Jacqueline in Gounod's ''[[Le m\u00e9decin malgr\u00e9 lui]]'', the mother in Charpentier's ''[[Louise]]'', the title role in ''[[Mignon]]'' by [[Ambroise Thomas]], Genevi\u00e8ve in Debussy's ''[[Pell\u00e9as et M\u00e9lisande]]'', Panttasil\u00e9e in Xavier Leroux's ''[[La reine Fiammette]]'', Rosette in Massenet's ''[[Manon]]'', Margared in Lalo's ''[[Le roi d\u2019Ys]]'', the title role in Puccini's ''[[Tosca]]'', Salud in de Falla's ''[[La vida breve]]'', and Popp\u00e9e in a French-language version of Monteverdi's ''[[L\u2019incoronazione di Poppea]]''.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1730}}\n\nShe participated in six world premieres, among them Magdeleine in [[Antoine Mariotte]]\u2019s ''Gargantua'', Ninon in Hector Fraggi's ''A quoi r\u00eaent les jeunes filles'', and the title role in [[Darius Milhaud]]\u2019s ''Esther de Carpentras''.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\nShe made her debut with the [[Paris Opera]] at the Palais Garnier on 13 October 1936 in the title role of Massenet's ''[[Herodiade]]''. As part of that company she also sang Ortrud in Wagner's ''[[Lohengrin (opera)|Lohengrin]]'', Br\u00fcnhilde in ''[[Die Walk\u00fcre]]'', Marguerite in ''[[La Damnation de Faust]]'' by Berlioz, Margared in ''Le Roi d\u2019Ys'' and Marina in Mussorgsky's ''[[Boris Godunov (opera)|Boris Godunov]]''.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} She appeared as a guest in Belgium, at the [[Royal Opera House]] in London, and in the Netherlands, Hungary, Monte Carlo, North Africa, Romania, and Switzerland.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1730}}\n\nShe had a powerful voice with exceptional musicality and an excellent technique.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} Having trained as a pianist, she functioned as an accompanist for her mother's lessons with students. Richard Davis noted that [[Marjorie Lawrence]] was surprised to discover that the person accompanying her during C\u00e9cile Gilly's lessons was her daughter, who then became the teacher responsible for teaching Lawrence actual roles.{{sfn|Davis|2012|p=38}}\n\nOn her retirement from the stage in 1951 she became the chair of the [[Conservatoire de Paris]].  She remained with the Conservatoire until her retirement in 1976.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1731}}{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\nGilly was married to baritone [[Louis Musy]].{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|p=1730}} She died on 30 March 1977 in Paris.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works consulted==\n*{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Richard Michael|title=Wotan's Daughter: The Life of Marjorie Lawrence|location=Kent Town, S. Australia|publisher=Wakefield Press|year=2012|isbn=9781743052105|ref = harv}}\n*{{citation|last=Gourret|first=Jean|title=Dictionnaire des cantatrices de l\u2019op\u00e9ra de Paris|location=Paris|publisher=Editions Albatros|year=1987|oclc= 489575054}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Kutsch\n| first = K. J.\n| authorlink = Karl Josef Kutsch\n| last2 = Riemens\n| first2 = Leo\n| authorlink2 = Leo Riemens\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dsfq_5dFeL0C&pg=PA1730\n| title = Gilly, Ren\u00e9e\n| work = [[Gro\u00dfes S\u00e4ngerlexikon]]\n| publisher = [[Walter de Gruyter]]\n| edition = 4th\n| language = de\n| year = 2012\n| pages = 1730\u20131731\n| isbn = 978-3-59-844088-5\n| ref = harv\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB portal|135441773}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilly, Ren\u00e9e}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:Opera singers]]\n[[Category:French operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French opera singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women opera singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Paris]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ren\u00e9e Gilly\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1906|04|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Paris, France\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1977|03|31|1906|04|29|df=y}}\n| death_place = Paris, France\n| other_names =\n| education   =\n| occupation  = {{plainlist|\n* Operatic [[mezzo-soprano]]\n* Academic teacher\n}}\n| spouse      = [[Louis Musy]]\n| parents     = [[Dinh Gilly]], [[C\u00e9cile Gilly]]\n| nationality = [[France]]\n}}\n'''Ren\u00e9e Gilly''' (19 April 1906 \u2013 31 March 1977) was a French operatic [[mezzo-soprano]]. She was a long-time principal member of the [[Op\u00e9ra-Comique]], where she performed leading roles such as Massenet's [[Werther|Charlotte]], Mascagni's [[Cavalleria Rusticana|Santuzza]], and Bizet's [[Carmen]]. She appeared in world premieres and sang as a guest at major opera houses in Europe.\n\n== Career ==\nGilly was born in Paris, the daughter of [[baritone]] [[Dinh Gilly]] and mezzo-soprano [[C\u00e9cile Gilly]].{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}  At the age of four she began piano studies with [[Marguerite Long]].{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} \nIn 1922 at the age of 16 she undertook a series of piano recitals in England. She also served as an accompanist to her father, who participated in a series of conferences concerning singing.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} At the suggestion of [[Pierre-Barth\u00e9lemy Gheusi]] (later director of the [[Op\u00e9ra-Comique]]) she took up singing, studying with both her father and her mother.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|p=1730}}\n\nShe made her debut at the Op\u00e9ra-Comique in the role of Charlotte in Massenet\u2019s ''[[Werther]]'' on 16 September 1933 and became one of the company's central  performers.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} Among her roles there were Bizet's [[Carmen]], Santuzza in Mascagni's ''[[Cavalleria Rusticana]]'', Toinette in [[Xavier Leroux]]'s ''Le Chemineau'', Dulcin\u00e9e in Massenet's ''[[Don Quichotte]]'', Jacqueline in Gounod's ''[[Le m\u00e9decin malgr\u00e9 lui]]'', the mother in Charpentier's ''[[Louise]]'', the title role in ''[[Mignon]]'' by [[Ambroise Thomas]], Genevi\u00e8ve in Debussy's ''[[Pell\u00e9as et M\u00e9lisande]]'', Panttasil\u00e9e in Xavier Leroux's ''[[La reine Fiammette]]'', Rosette in Massenet's ''[[Manon]]'', Margared in Lalo's ''[[Le roi d\u2019Ys]]'', the title role in Puccini's ''[[Tosca]]'', Salud in de Falla's ''[[La vida breve]]'', and Popp\u00e9e in a French-language version of Monteverdi's ''[[L\u2019incoronazione di Poppea]]''.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1730}}\n\nShe participated in six world premieres, among them Magdeleine in [[Antoine Mariotte]]\u2019s ''Gargantua'', Ninon in Hector Fraggi's ''A quoi r\u00eaent les jeunes filles'', and the title role in [[Darius Milhaud]]\u2019s ''Esther de Carpentras''.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\nShe made her debut with the [[Paris Opera]] at the Palais Garnier on 13 October 1936 in the title role of Massenet's ''[[Herodiade]]''. As part of that company she also sang Ortrud in Wagner's ''[[Lohengrin (opera)|Lohengrin]]'', Br\u00fcnhilde in ''[[Die Walk\u00fcre]]'', Marguerite in ''[[La Damnation de Faust]]'' by Berlioz, Margared in ''Le Roi d\u2019Ys'' and Marina in Mussorgsky's ''[[Boris Godunov (opera)|Boris Godunov]]''.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} She appeared as a guest in Belgium, at the [[Royal Opera House]] in London, and in the Netherlands, Hungary, Monte Carlo, North Africa, Romania, and Switzerland.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1730}}\n\nShe had a powerful voice with exceptional musicality and an excellent technique.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} Having trained as a pianist, she functioned as an accompanist for her mother's lessons with students. Richard Davis noted that [[Marjorie Lawrence]] was surprised to discover that the person accompanying her during C\u00e9cile Gilly's lessons was her daughter, who then became the teacher responsible for teaching Lawrence actual roles.{{sfn|Davis|2012|p=38}}\n\nOn her retirement from the stage in 1951 she became the chair of the [[Conservatoire de Paris]].  She remained with the Conservatoire until her retirement in 1976.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1731}}{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\nGilly was married to baritone [[Louis Musy]].{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|p=1730}}\nShe died on 30 March 1977 in Paris.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works consulted==\n*{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Richard Michael|title=Wotan's Daughter: The Life of Marjorie Lawrence|location=Kent Town, S. Australia|publisher=Wakefield Press|year=2012|isbn=9781743052105|ref = harv}}\n*{{citation|last=Gourret|first=Jean|title=Dictionnaire des cantatrices de l\u2019op\u00e9ra de Paris|location=Paris|publisher=Editions Albatros|year=1987|oclc= 489575054}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Kutsch\n| first = K. J.\n| authorlink = Karl Josef Kutsch\n| last2 = Riemens\n| first2 = Leo\n| authorlink2 = Leo Riemens\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dsfq_5dFeL0C&pg=PA1730\n| title = Gilly, Ren\u00e9e\n| work = [[Gro\u00dfes S\u00e4ngerlexikon]]\n| publisher = [[Walter de Gruyter]]\n| edition = 4th\n| language = de\n| year = 2012\n| pages = 1730\u20131731\n| isbn = 978-3-59-844088-5\n| ref = harv\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB portal|135441773}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilly, Ren\u00e9e}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:Opera singers]]\n[[Category:French operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French opera singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women opera singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Paris]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9e_Gilly"}
{"title_page": "\u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu", "text_new": "{{short description|Vietnamese footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = \u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu\n| fullname = \u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu\n| image = [[https://cdn.soccerwiki.org/images/player/102398.png]]\n| image_size = [[File:Trivela.jpg|250px|left|thumb|\n| caption = Doan Van Hau (white) was playing in a match of [[Vietnam olympic national football team]]]] \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1999|04|19}}\n| birth_place = [[H\u01b0ng H\u00e0 District|H\u01b0ng H\u00e0]], [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province|Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh]], [[Vietnam]]\n| height = {{height|meters=1.85}}<ref>{{in lang|vi}} [https://webthethao.vn/cac-doi-tuyen-quoc-gia/chieu-cao-doi-tuyen-viet-nam-2019-nho-nhung-co-vo-103297.htm Chi\u1ec1u cao \u0111\u1ed9i tuy\u1ec3n Vi\u1ec7t Nam 2019: Nh\u1ecf nh\u01b0ng c\u00f3 v\u00f5]</ref>\n| currentclub = [[SC Heerenveen]] (on loan from  [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i FC]])\n| clubnumber = 15\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = 2010\u20132017\n| youthclubs1 = [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i FC]]\n| years1 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i FC]]\n| caps1 = 52\n| goals1 = 6\n| years2 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[SC Heerenveen]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2016\u20132017\n| nationalteam1 = [[Vietnam national under-19 football team|Vietnam U19]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 18\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 2017\n| nationalteam2 = [[Vietnam national under-20 football team|Vietnam U20]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 5\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2017\u2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[Vietnam national under-23 football team|Vietnam U23]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 30\n| nationalgoals3 = 5\n| nationalyears4 = 2017\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 23\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| medaltemplates = {{medal|Team|Vietnam under-23}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[AFC U-23 Championship]]}}\n{{medal|RU|[[2018 AFC U-23 Championship|2018 China]]|[[Vietnam national under-23 football team|Vietnam U23]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[AFF Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2018 AFF Championship|2018 South East Asia]]|[[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]]}}\n| pcupdate = 2 September 2019\n| ntupdate = 19 December 2019\n}}\n\n'''\u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu''' (born 19 April 1999) is a Vietnamese [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]] for [[Eredivisie]] club [[SC Heerenveen]] on loan from [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]] and [[Vietnam national football team]]. \n\n==Club career==\nHe became a regular part of his club [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]] in 2017 when he was just 17, making him one of the youngest Vietnamese players to debut in the [[V.League 1]]. His performance was considered as one of the most impressive among youngsters in Vietnam. He won the [[2018 V.League 1]] and 2018 Vietnamese Super Cup with [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]]. He was also in the 2018 V.League 1 Team of The Season.\n\nOn 2 September 2019, he joined [[SC Heerenveen]] in the Dutch [[Eredivisie]] on a 1 year loan from [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]]. He made his first-team debut when coming from the bench on 2-0 win over [[Roda_JC_Kerkrade|Roda JC]] in [[KNVB_Cup|KNVB Cup]] on 17th December 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eenvoudige bekerzege, debuut Van Hau |url=https://www.sc-heerenveen.nl/nieuws/eenvoudige-bekerzege-debuut-van-hau/10 |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Trivela.jpg|250px|left|thumb|Doan Van Hau (white) was playing in a match of [[Vietnam national football team]]]] \n===U-19 and U-20 World Cup===\n\u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu made his first international appearance for the [[Vietnam national under-20 football team]] in [[2016 AFC U-19 Championship]] at the age of 16. In the match against [[North Korea national under-20 football team|North Korea]], one of Asia's major youth giant and runners-up of previous [[2014 AFC U-19 Championship]], he scored in an astonishing goal from distance as Vietnam registered their historic 2\u20131 win over North Korea, set up the historic journey as Vietnam would eventually make their first major [[FIFA]] 11-men football debut, the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vietnamplus.vn/can-canh-sieu-pham-cua-doan-van-hau-vao-luoi-u19-trieu-tien/410997.vnp|title=C\u1eadn c\u1ea3nh si\u00eau ph\u1ea9m c\u1ee7a \u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu v\u00e0o l\u01b0\u1edbi U19 Tri\u1ec1u Ti\u00ean - B\u00f3ng \u0111\u00e1 - Vietnam+ (VietnamPlus)|last=VietnamPlus|date=15 October 2016|website=VietnamPlus|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref> In the U-20 World Cup, he didn't score any goals as the team exited with only a point.\n\n===U-22, to U23 and Olympics===\n\u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu's talents got himself promoted to the U-22, U23 and Olympic team in spite of his age. He made his debut on the U-22 team in the CFA friendly tournament in China, and scored a goal against Uzbekistan in a 1\u20133 defeat. He would later participate in the [[Football at the 2017 Southeast Asian Games|2017 SEA Games]], scored two goals but his [[Vietnam national under-23 football team|U-22 team]] had to end up in poor note, being eliminated from the group stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webthethao.vn/sea-games-29/doan-van-hau-va-man-chao-san-dang-nho-o-sea-games-29-42006.htm|title=\u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu v\u00e0 m\u00e0n ch\u00e0o s\u00e2n \u0111\u00e1ng nh\u1edb \u1edf SEA Games 29|website=webthethao.vn|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, his role became prominent in the [[2018 AFC U-23 Championship]]. Although scoring no goal, he gave a magnificent performance, assisted for [[Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ea3i (footballer, born 1997)|Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ea3i]] to score in the 1\u20132 defeat to [[South Korea national under-23 football team|South Korea]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/vn/tintuc/quang-hai-lap-sieu-pham-u23-viet-nam-suyt-gay-dia-chan-truoc-u23-/f2rm76l6y6nc10k7tnq4cqc72|title=Quang H\u1ea3i l\u1eadp si\u00eau ph\u1ea9m, U23 Vi\u1ec7t Nam su\u00fdt t\u1ea1o \u0111\u1ecba ch\u1ea5n tr\u01b0\u1edbc U23 H\u00e0n Qu\u1ed1c |website=Goal.com|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref> and his tackles against [[Iraq national under-23 football team|Iraq]] as Vietnam advanced to their first final in any AFC tournament, which earned reputation by Dutch press as \"Doan Van [[Gareth Bale|Bale]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voetbalzone.nl/doc.asp?uid=321971|title=\u2018Doan Van Bale\u2019 maakt indruk: \u2018Ik zou dan voor PSV kiezen\u2019|date=9 February 2018|website=Voetbalzone|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Vinaphone Cup 2018]], he scored a [[Curl (football)|trivela goal]] that helped his native Vietnam beat [[Oman national under-23 football team|Oman]] 1\u20130.<ref>https://news.zing.vn/olympic-vn-vs-olympic-oman-1-0-doan-van-hau-ghi-ban-dep-mat-post864983.html</ref>\n\n\u0110o\u00e0n played a vital role in Vietnam's [[SEA Games 2019|SEA Games 30]] campaign, scoring two goals in a 3-0 victory against [[Indonesia national under-23 football team|Olympic Indonesia]] on the finale.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|February 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | National Cup\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season !! Club !! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|[[2017 V.League 1|2017]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i FC]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[V.League 1]]||11||1||0||0||1<ref group=lower-alpha>Appearances in [[AFC Cup]]</ref>||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||1\n|-\n|[[2018 V.League 1|2018]]||20||5||0||0||0||0||1<ref group=lower-alpha>Appearances in [[Vietnamese National Football Super Cup|Vietnamese Super Cup]]</ref>||0||21||5\n|-\n|[[2019 V.League 1|2019]]||21||0||0||0||11<ref group=lower-alpha>Two appearances in [[AFC Champions League]] play-off round and nine appearances in [[AFC Cup]]</ref>||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Totals!!52!!6!!0!!0!!12!!0!!1!!0!!65!!6\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Eredivisie|2019\u201320]]||rowspan=\"1\"|[[SC Heerenveen]] (loan)||rowspan=\"1\"|[[Eredivisie]]||0||0||1||0||colspan=\"4\"|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!52!!6!!1!!0!!12!!0!!1!!0!!66!!6\n|-\n|}\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==International==\n====Vietnam U-23====\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1 || rowspan=\"2\"| 15 August 2017 || rowspan=\"2\"| [[MP Selayang Stadium|Selayang Municipal Council Stadium]], [[Selayang]], [[Malaysia]]  || rowspan=\"2\"| {{fbu|23|TLS}} ||'''1'''\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\"| 4\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\"| [[Football at the 2017 Southeast Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2017 Southeast Asian Games]]\n|-\n| 2 || '''3'''\u20130 \n|-\n| 3 || 05 August 2018 || [[My Dinh Stadium]], [[Hanoi]], [[Vietnam]] || {{fbu|23|OMA}}|| '''1'''\u20130 || 1\u20130 || [[2018 Vinaphone Cup]]\n|-\n| 4 || rowspan=\"2\"| 10 December 2019 || rowspan=\"2\"| [[Rizal Memorial Stadium]], [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]  || rowspan=\"2\"| {{fbu|23|TLS}} ||'''1'''\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\"| 3\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\"| [[Football at the 2019 Southeast Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2019 Southeast Asian Games]]\n|-\n| 5 || '''3'''\u20130 \n|-\n|}\n\n====Vietnam====\n{{updated|match played 19 November 2019}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"11\"|[[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]]\n|-\n|2017||3||0\n|-\n|2018||8||0\n|-\n|2019||12||0\n|-\n!colspan=1|Total||23||0\n|}\n\n===Senior team===\nDue to his impressive performances at youth teams, he was named on [[Park Hang-seo]] squad for the [[2018 AFF Championship]] and played an instrumental role on helping Vietnam to gain the second title, assisting important goals for his teammates which made him one of eleven main players of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/asian-football/aff-suzuki-cup/988817/aff-suzuki-cup-2018-honour-to-represent-vietnam-makes-me-proud-says-doan-van-hau/|title=AFF Suzuki Cup 2018: 'Honour to represent Vietnam,' says Doan Van Hau|date=2 December 2018|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, it was the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup]], in which he was one of the youngest players in the tournament at the age of 19, that saw him earned reputation. His notable performance was against [[Jordan national football team|Jordan]], where he prevented a number of Jordanian attacks as Vietnam marched to the quarter-finals for the second consecutive time.<ref>https://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/sports/216766/vietnam-s-doan-van-hau-named-one-of-the-top-10-players-in-asian-cup-round-of-16.html</ref> He was later named as one of 10 best young players at the tournament.<ref>https://vietnamnews.vn/sports/484648/hai-hau-best-young-players-at-asian-cup.html</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n\n'''[[H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i F.C.|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i FC]]'''\n*'''[[V.League 1]]''': \n:{{Gold1}} '''Winners :'''      [[2018 V.League 1|2018]], [[2019 V.League 1|2019]]\n\n*'''[[Vietnamese Super Cup]]''': \n:{{Gold1}} '''Winners :'''      2018\n\n===International===\n'''[[Vietnam national under-19 football team|Vietnam U-19]]'''\n*'''[[AFF U-19 Youth Championship]]''': {{Bronze3}} Third place : (2016)\n*'''[[AFC U-19 Championship]]''': {{Bronze3}} Third place : ([[2016 AFC U-19 Championship|2016]])\n'''[[Vietnam national under-23 football team|Vietnam U-23]]'''\n*'''[[AFC U-23 Championship]]''': {{Silver2}} Runners-up  ([[2018 AFC U-23 Championship|2018]])\n*'''[[Football at the Southeast Asian Games|Southeast Asian Games]]''': {{Gold1}} '''Champions''' ([[Football at the 2019 Southeast Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2019]])\n'''[[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]]'''\n*'''[[AFF Championship]]''': {{Gold1}} '''Champions''' ([[2018 AFF Championship|2018]])\n\n===Individual===\n* '''[[ASEAN Football Federation|AFF Youth Player of the Year]]''': [[ASEAN Football Federation#AFF Youth Player of the Year|2017]]\n* '''[[Vietnamese Golden Ball|Youth Vietnamese Player of the Year]]''': [[Vietnamese Golden Ball#Young Player of the Year|2017, 2018]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!--{{Hanoi F.C. squad}}-->\n{{SC Heerenveen squad}}\n{{Vietnam squad 2019 AFC Asian Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doan, Van Hau}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:V.League 1 players]]\n[[Category:H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i F.C. players]]\n[[Category:SC Heerenveen players]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2018 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:2019 AFC Asian Cup players]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2017 Southeast Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games competitors for Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2019 Southeast Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Southeast Asian Games medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Southeast Asian Games gold medalists for Vietnam]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Vietnamese footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = \u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu\n| fullname = \u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu\n| image = [[https://cdn.soccerwiki.org/images/player/102398.png]]\n| image_size = [[File:Trivela.jpg|250px|left|thumb|\n| caption = Doan Van Hau (white) was playing in a match of [[Vietnam olympic national football team]]]] \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1999|04|19}}\n| birth_place = [[H\u01b0ng H\u00e0 District|H\u01b0ng H\u00e0]], [[Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province|Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh]], [[Vietnam]]\n| height = {{height|meters=1.85}}<ref>{{in lang|vi}} [https://webthethao.vn/cac-doi-tuyen-quoc-gia/chieu-cao-doi-tuyen-viet-nam-2019-nho-nhung-co-vo-103297.htm Chi\u1ec1u cao \u0111\u1ed9i tuy\u1ec3n Vi\u1ec7t Nam 2019: Nh\u1ecf nh\u01b0ng c\u00f3 v\u00f5]</ref>\n| currentclub = [[SC Heerenveen]] (on loan from  [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i FC]])\n| clubnumber = 15\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = 2010\u20132017\n| youthclubs1 = [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i FC]]\n| years1 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i FC]]\n| caps1 = 52\n| goals1 = 6\n| years2 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[SC Heerenveen]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2016\u20132017\n| nationalteam1 = [[Vietnam national under-19 football team|Vietnam U19]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 18\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 2017\n| nationalteam2 = [[Vietnam national under-20 football team|Vietnam U20]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 5\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2017\u2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[Vietnam national under-23 football team|Vietnam U23]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 30\n| nationalgoals3 = 5\n| nationalyears4 = 2017\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 23\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| medaltemplates = {{medal|Team|Vietnam under-23}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[AFC U-23 Championship]]}}\n{{medal|RU|[[2018 AFC U-23 Championship|2018 China]]|[[Vietnam national under-23 football team|Vietnam U23]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[AFF Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2018 AFF Championship|2018 South East Asia]]|[[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]]}}\n| pcupdate = 2 September 2019\n| ntupdate = 19 December 2019\n}}\n\n'''\u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu''' (born 19 April 1999) is a Vietnamese [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]] for [[Eredivisie]] club [[SC Heerenveen]] on loan from [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]] and [[Vietnam national football team]]. \n\n==Club career==\nHe became a regular part of his club [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]] in 2017 when he was just 17, making him one of the youngest Vietnamese players to debut in the [[V.League 1]]. His performance was considered as among one of the most impressive among youngsters in Vietnam. He won the [[2018 V.League 1]] and 2018 Vietnamese Super Cup with [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]]. He was also in the 2018 V.League 1 Team of The Season.\n\nOn 2 September 2019, he joined [[SC Heerenveen]] in the Dutch [[Eredivisie]] on a 1 year loan from [[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]]. He made his first-team debut when coming from the bench on 2-0 win over [[Roda_JC_Kerkrade|Roda JC]] in [[KNVB_Cup|KNVB Cup]] on 17th December 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eenvoudige bekerzege, debuut Van Hau |url=https://www.sc-heerenveen.nl/nieuws/eenvoudige-bekerzege-debuut-van-hau/10 |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Trivela.jpg|250px|left|thumb|Doan Van Hau (white) was playing in a match of [[Vietnam national football team]]]] \n===U-19 and U-20 World Cup===\n\u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu made his first international appearance for the [[Vietnam national under-20 football team]] in [[2016 AFC U-19 Championship]] at the age of 16. In the match against [[North Korea national under-20 football team|North Korea]], one of Asia's major youth giant and runners-up of previous [[2014 AFC U-19 Championship]], he scored in an astonishing goal from distance as Vietnam registered their historic 2\u20131 win over North Korea, set up the historic journey as Vietnam would eventually make their first major [[FIFA]] 11-men football debut, the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vietnamplus.vn/can-canh-sieu-pham-cua-doan-van-hau-vao-luoi-u19-trieu-tien/410997.vnp|title=C\u1eadn c\u1ea3nh si\u00eau ph\u1ea9m c\u1ee7a \u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu v\u00e0o l\u01b0\u1edbi U19 Tri\u1ec1u Ti\u00ean - B\u00f3ng \u0111\u00e1 - Vietnam+ (VietnamPlus)|last=VietnamPlus|date=15 October 2016|website=VietnamPlus|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref> In the U-20 World Cup, he didn't score any goals as the team exited with only a point.\n\n===U-22, to U23 and Olympics===\n\u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu's talents got himself promoted to the U-22, U23 and Olympic team in spite of his age. He made his debut on the U-22 team in the CFA friendly tournament in China, and scored a goal against Uzbekistan in a 1\u20133 defeat. He would later participate in the [[Football at the 2017 Southeast Asian Games|2017 SEA Games]], scored two goals but his [[Vietnam national under-23 football team|U-22 team]] had to end up in poor note, being eliminated from the group stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webthethao.vn/sea-games-29/doan-van-hau-va-man-chao-san-dang-nho-o-sea-games-29-42006.htm|title=\u0110o\u00e0n V\u0103n H\u1eadu v\u00e0 m\u00e0n ch\u00e0o s\u00e2n \u0111\u00e1ng nh\u1edb \u1edf SEA Games 29|website=webthethao.vn|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, his role became prominent in the [[2018 AFC U-23 Championship]]. Although scoring no goal, he gave a magnificent performance, assisted for [[Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ea3i (footballer, born 1997)|Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ea3i]] to score in the 1\u20132 defeat to [[South Korea national under-23 football team|South Korea]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/vn/tintuc/quang-hai-lap-sieu-pham-u23-viet-nam-suyt-gay-dia-chan-truoc-u23-/f2rm76l6y6nc10k7tnq4cqc72|title=Quang H\u1ea3i l\u1eadp si\u00eau ph\u1ea9m, U23 Vi\u1ec7t Nam su\u00fdt t\u1ea1o \u0111\u1ecba ch\u1ea5n tr\u01b0\u1edbc U23 H\u00e0n Qu\u1ed1c |website=Goal.com|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref> and his tackles against [[Iraq national under-23 football team|Iraq]] as Vietnam advanced to their first final in any AFC tournament, which earned reputation by Dutch press as \"Doan Van [[Gareth Bale|Bale]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voetbalzone.nl/doc.asp?uid=321971|title=\u2018Doan Van Bale\u2019 maakt indruk: \u2018Ik zou dan voor PSV kiezen\u2019|date=9 February 2018|website=Voetbalzone|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Vinaphone Cup 2018]], he scored a [[Curl (football)|trivela goal]] that helped his native Vietnam beat [[Oman national under-23 football team|Oman]] 1\u20130.<ref>https://news.zing.vn/olympic-vn-vs-olympic-oman-1-0-doan-van-hau-ghi-ban-dep-mat-post864983.html</ref>\n\n\u0110o\u00e0n played a vital role in Vietnam's [[SEA Games 2019|SEA Games 30]] campaign, scoring two goals in a 3-0 victory against [[Indonesia national under-23 football team|Olympic Indonesia]] on the finale.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|February 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | National Cup\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season !! Club !! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|[[2017 V.League 1|2017]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Hanoi FC|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i FC]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[V.League 1]]||11||1||0||0||1<ref group=lower-alpha>Appearances in [[AFC Cup]]</ref>||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||1\n|-\n|[[2018 V.League 1|2018]]||20||5||0||0||0||0||1<ref group=lower-alpha>Appearances in [[Vietnamese National Football Super Cup|Vietnamese Super Cup]]</ref>||0||21||5\n|-\n|[[2019 V.League 1|2019]]||21||0||0||0||11<ref group=lower-alpha>Two appearances in [[AFC Champions League]] play-off round and nine appearances in [[AFC Cup]]</ref>||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Totals!!52!!6!!0!!0!!12!!0!!1!!0!!65!!6\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Eredivisie|2019\u201320]]||rowspan=\"1\"|[[SC Heerenveen]] (loan)||rowspan=\"1\"|[[Eredivisie]]||0||0||1||0||colspan=\"4\"|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!52!!6!!1!!0!!12!!0!!1!!0!!66!!6\n|-\n|}\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==International==\n====Vietnam U-23====\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1 || rowspan=\"2\"| 15 August 2017 || rowspan=\"2\"| [[MP Selayang Stadium|Selayang Municipal Council Stadium]], [[Selayang]], [[Malaysia]]  || rowspan=\"2\"| {{fbu|23|TLS}} ||'''1'''\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\"| 4\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\"| [[Football at the 2017 Southeast Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2017 Southeast Asian Games]]\n|-\n| 2 || '''3'''\u20130 \n|-\n| 3 || 05 August 2018 || [[My Dinh Stadium]], [[Hanoi]], [[Vietnam]] || {{fbu|23|OMA}}|| '''1'''\u20130 || 1\u20130 || [[2018 Vinaphone Cup]]\n|-\n| 4 || rowspan=\"2\"| 10 December 2019 || rowspan=\"2\"| [[Rizal Memorial Stadium]], [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]  || rowspan=\"2\"| {{fbu|23|TLS}} ||'''1'''\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\"| 3\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\"| [[Football at the 2019 Southeast Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2019 Southeast Asian Games]]\n|-\n| 5 || '''3'''\u20130 \n|-\n|}\n\n====Vietnam====\n{{updated|match played 19 November 2019}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"11\"|[[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]]\n|-\n|2017||3||0\n|-\n|2018||8||0\n|-\n|2019||12||0\n|-\n!colspan=1|Total||23||0\n|}\n\n===Senior team===\nDue to his impressive performances at youth teams, he was named on [[Park Hang-seo]] squad for the [[2018 AFF Championship]] and played an instrumental role on helping Vietnam to gain the second title, assisting important goals for his teammates which made him one of eleven main players of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/asian-football/aff-suzuki-cup/988817/aff-suzuki-cup-2018-honour-to-represent-vietnam-makes-me-proud-says-doan-van-hau/|title=AFF Suzuki Cup 2018: 'Honour to represent Vietnam,' says Doan Van Hau|date=2 December 2018|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, it was the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup]], in which he was one of the youngest players in the tournament at the age of 19, that saw him earned reputation. His notable performance was against [[Jordan national football team|Jordan]], where he prevented a number of Jordanian attacks as Vietnam marched to the quarter-finals for the second consecutive time.<ref>https://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/sports/216766/vietnam-s-doan-van-hau-named-one-of-the-top-10-players-in-asian-cup-round-of-16.html</ref> He was later named as one of 10 best young players at the tournament.<ref>https://vietnamnews.vn/sports/484648/hai-hau-best-young-players-at-asian-cup.html</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n\n'''[[H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i F.C.|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i FC]]'''\n*'''[[V.League 1]]''': \n:{{Gold1}} '''Winners :'''      [[2018 V.League 1|2018]], [[2019 V.League 1|2019]]\n\n*'''[[Vietnamese Super Cup]]''': \n:{{Gold1}} '''Winners :'''      2018\n\n===International===\n'''[[Vietnam national under-19 football team|Vietnam U-19]]'''\n*'''[[AFF U-19 Youth Championship]]''': {{Bronze3}} Third place : (2016)\n*'''[[AFC U-19 Championship]]''': {{Bronze3}} Third place : ([[2016 AFC U-19 Championship|2016]])\n'''[[Vietnam national under-23 football team|Vietnam U-23]]'''\n*'''[[AFC U-23 Championship]]''': {{Silver2}} Runners-up  ([[2018 AFC U-23 Championship|2018]])\n*'''[[Football at the Southeast Asian Games|Southeast Asian Games]]''': {{Gold1}} '''Champions''' ([[Football at the 2019 Southeast Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|2019]])\n'''[[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]]'''\n*'''[[AFF Championship]]''': {{Gold1}} '''Champions''' ([[2018 AFF Championship|2018]])\n\n===Individual===\n* '''[[ASEAN Football Federation|AFF Youth Player of the Year]]''': [[ASEAN Football Federation#AFF Youth Player of the Year|2017]]\n* '''[[Vietnamese Golden Ball|Youth Vietnamese Player of the Year]]''': [[Vietnamese Golden Ball#Young Player of the Year|2017, 2018]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!--{{Hanoi F.C. squad}}-->\n{{SC Heerenveen squad}}\n{{Vietnam squad 2019 AFC Asian Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doan, Van Hau}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh Province]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:V.League 1 players]]\n[[Category:H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i F.C. players]]\n[[Category:SC Heerenveen players]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2018 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:2019 AFC Asian Cup players]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2017 Southeast Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games competitors for Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2019 Southeast Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Southeast Asian Games medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Southeast Asian Games gold medalists for Vietnam]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reword - you can't be \"among one\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C4%90o%C3%A0n_V%C4%83n_H%E1%BA%ADu"}
{"title_page": "1941 Dartmouth Indians football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| sport = football\n| year = 1941\n| team = Dartmouth Indians\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| conference = Independent\n| record = 5\u20134\n| head_coach = [[Tuss McLaughry]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| stadium = [[Memorial Field (Dartmouth)|Memorial Field]]\n| off_scheme = \n| def_scheme = \n| captain = \n| stadium = [[Memorial Field (Dartmouth)|Memorial Field]]\n}}\n{{1941 Eastern college football independents records}}\nThe '''1941 Dartmouth Indians football team''' represented [[Dartmouth College]] during the [[1941 college football season]].  In its first season under head coach [[Tuss McLaughry]], the team compiled a 5\u20134 record and was outscored by a total of 146 to 104.<ref name=SR>{{cite web|title=1941 Dartmouth Big Green Schedule and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=SR/College Football|accessdate=September 11, 2019|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/dartmouth/1941-schedule.html}}</ref> The team played its home games at [[Memorial Field (Dartmouth)|Memorial Field]] in [[Hanover, New Hampshire]]. \n\nQuarterback John Krol and halfback Douglas were selected by the [[United Press]] as second-team players on the 1941 All-New England football team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Harvard Linemen Land Five Berths on All-N.E. Team|newspaper=The Boston Globe|date=November 26, 1941|page=23|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/36571401/harvard_linemen_land_five_berths_on/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| attend = yes\n| source = yes\n| rankyear = 1941\n| poll = AP\n\n|September 27||{{cfb link|year=1941|team=Norwich Cadets|title=Norwich}}|[[Memorial Field (Dartmouth)|Memorial Field]]|[[Hanover, New Hampshire|Hanover, NH]]|W 35-0||<ref>{{cite news|title=Dartmouth Spanks Norwich, 35-0|newspaper=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=September 28, 1941|page=2S|url=https://www.n